</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B9F369CFFA6215ADA0BFE95FC4F633E" blockId="43.[827,1468,183,652]" pageId="43" pageNumber="2825">
The description is that of the species [
<bibRefCitation id="EFB14B6DFFA6215ADDECFE95FB44637C" author="Orla-Jensen S." box="[1243,1259,259,283]" pageId="43" pageNumber="2825" refId="ref59849" refString="2. Orla-Jensen S. The lactic acid bacteria. Copenhagen: Andr Fred HOst and Son; 1919." type="book" year="1919">2</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="EFB14B6DFFA6215ADDC0FE95FA8C637C" author="Bergey DH &amp; Harrison F &amp; Breed R &amp; Hammer F." box="[1271,1315,259,283]" pageId="43" pageNumber="2825" refId="ref69986" refString="231. Bergey DH, Harrison F, Breed R, Hammer F. Bergey's Manual of Determinative Bacteriology, 1 st ed. Baltimore: The Williams &amp; Wilkins Co.,; 1923." type="book" year="1923">231</bibRefCitation>
]. The genome size of the 
<typeStatus id="549B883EFFA6215ADA84FEB5FC4E635C" box="[947,993,291,315]" pageId="43" pageNumber="2825">type</typeStatus>
strain is 3.45 Mbp. The mol% G+C content of DNA is 44.2.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B9F369CFFA6215ADA0BFEF9FA1963A2" blockId="43.[827,1468,183,652]" pageId="43" pageNumber="2825">Isolated from dairy products and dairy environments, silage, sauerkraut, pickled vegetables, sour- dough, cow dung, the human mouth, intestinal tract and stools, and from sewage.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
